<subSubSection id="498B657AFF8ADD1740E6FBEAFD5C91E7" pageId="1" pageNumber="224" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="012E36F1FF8ADD1740E6FBEAFCB693A7" blockId="1.[136,1452,1080,2043]" pageId="1" pageNumber="224">
Diagnosis: Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF8ADD1741E2FBEAFDDF936E" authorityName="Muller-Argoviensis" authorityYear="1872" box="[441,583,1080,1106]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="224" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stenoloba">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF8ADD1741E2FBEAFDDF936E" box="[441,583,1080,1106]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="224">A. stenoloba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs from it by being a subshrub of up to 
<quantity id="C6699B14FF8ADD174425FBEAFB34936F" box="[1150,1196,1080,1107]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="224" unit="m" value="1.0">1 m</quantity>
tall, with axillary and terminal pistillate inflorescences, pistillate flowers with free ovate-lanceolate sepals, pistillate bracts with cuneate base, and styles glabrous, ca. 12 times longer than the ovary.
</paragraph>
