<paragraph id="012E36F1FF88DD1540E6FA32FD6C9003" blockId="3.[136,1452,1288,2071]" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD1540E6FA32FE5292C6" bold="true" box="[189,458,1504,1530]" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">Taxonomic comments:</emphasis>
—The new species belongs to subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF88DD1543D4FA32FC6192C6" authorityName="Linnaeus (1753:" authorityYear="1003" box="[911,1017,1504,1530]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD1543D4FA32FC6192C6" box="[911,1017,1504,1530]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">Acalypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to the presence of sessile pistillate flowers and accrescent pistillate bracts. The species that 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF88DD15436BF9D6FC6E9122" authorityName="Mart. Gord., Fragoso &amp; K. Velasco" authorityYear="2022" box="[816,1014,1540,1566]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amithii">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD15436BF9D6FC6E9122" box="[816,1014,1540,1566]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">Acalypha amithii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles the most morphologically is 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF88DD1540FEF9FBFD39917E" authority="Muller-Argoviensis (1872: 41)" authorityName="Muller-Argoviensis" authorityPageNumber="41" authorityYear="1872" box="[165,673,1576,1603]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stenoloba">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD1540FEF9FBFEAD917E" box="[165,309,1576,1603]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">A. stenoloba</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="65004B00FF88DD154164F9FAFD39917E" author="Muller-Argoviensis, J." box="[319,673,1576,1602]" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" pagination="41 - 45" refId="ref2975" refString="Muller-Argoviensis, J. (1872) Euphorbiacearum species novae. Flora 55: 2 - 11, 24 - 28, 41 - 45." type="journal article" year="1872">Müller-Argoviensis (1872: 41)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, a 
<collectingCountry id="79867661FF88DD15429CF9FBFD62917F" box="[711,762,1577,1603]" name="Peru" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">Peru</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="79867661FF88DD154363F9FAFC12917E" box="[824,906,1576,1602]" name="Bolivia" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
endemic, which thrives in the Amazonian and Andean regions (
<bibRefCitation id="65004B00FF88DD154111F99EFE7A915A" author="Cardiel, J. M." box="[330,482,1612,1638]" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" pagination="405 - 414" refId="ref2648" refString="Cardiel, J. M. (2007) Catalogo de las especies peruanas de Acalypha Linnaeus (Euphorbiaceae). Fontqueria 55: 405 - 414." type="journal article" year="2007">Cardiel 2007</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="65004B00FF88DD1541B4F99EFDB4915A" author="Cardiel, J. M. &amp; Nee, M. &amp; Munoz-Rodriguez, P." box="[495,556,1612,1638]" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" pagination="152 - 177" refId="ref2737" refString="Cardiel, J. M., Nee, M. &amp; Munoz-Rodriguez, P. (2013) Synopsis of Acalypha L. (Euphorbiaceae) of Peru and Bolivia, with description of a new species. Anales del Jardin Botanico de Madrid 70: 152 - 177. https: // doi. org / 10.3989 / ajbm. 2366" type="journal article" year="2013">2013</bibRefCitation>
). Both species share the glabrous, petiolate, and penninerved leaves, unisexual inflorescences and pistillate bracts with 9 or less teeth. The new species differs from 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF88DD154411F9A3FB4F91B6" authorityName="Muller-Argoviensis" authorityYear="1872" box="[1098,1239,1648,1675]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stenoloba">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD154411F9A3FB4F91B6" box="[1098,1239,1648,1675]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">A. stenoloba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the habit, being a subshrub up to 
<quantity id="C6699B14FF88DD154111F946FEEE9193" box="[330,374,1684,1711]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" unit="m" value="1.0">1 m</quantity>
high (vs. shrubs or small trees up to 
<quantity id="C6699B14FF88DD154340F946FCDE9193" box="[795,838,1684,1711]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" unit="m" value="8.0">8 m</quantity>
high in 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF88DD1543FEF947FBAA9192" authorityName="Muller-Argoviensis" authorityYear="1872" box="[933,1074,1684,1711]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stenoloba">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD1543FEF947FBAA9192" box="[933,1074,1684,1711]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">A. stenoloba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); the leaves have 9 or more pairs of lateral nerves (vs. 7); the pistillate inflorescences are terminal and axillary (vs. only terminal); the pistillate sepals are completely free from each other (vs. connate at the base) and their shape is ovate-lanceolate (vs. triangular); the pistillate bracts are cuneate at the base (vs. cordate at the base); the styles are glabrous (
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD15443BF8D3FBE79026" box="[1120,1151,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">vs.</emphasis>
puberulent) and almost 12 times longer than the ovary (vs. almost 5 times longer).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="012E36F1FF88DD1540E6F89BFA1A9F2A" blockId="3.[136,1452,1288,2071]" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">
From the Mesoamerican species of 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF88DD154203F89AFD5A905E" authorityName="Linnaeus (1753:" authorityYear="1003" box="[600,706,1864,1890]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD154203F89AFD5A905E" box="[600,706,1864,1890]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">Acalypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF88DD154289F89BFCDA905E" authorityName="Mart. Gord., Fragoso &amp; K. Velasco" authorityYear="2022" box="[722,834,1864,1891]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amithii">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD154289F89BFCDA905E" box="[722,834,1864,1891]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">A. amithii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF88DD15439EF89BFB2D905E" authority="Hoffm." authorityName="Hoffm." box="[965,1205,1864,1891]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferdinandi">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD15439EF89BFBC3905E" box="[965,1115,1864,1891]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">A. ferdinandi</emphasis>
Hoffm.
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD15449CF89BFB45905E" box="[1223,1245,1865,1890]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="65004B00FF88DD1544BDF89BFF7690BB" author="Pax, F. &amp; Hoffmann, K." pageId="3" pageNumber="226" pagination="1 - 231" refId="ref3001" refString="Pax, F. &amp; Hoffmann, K. (1924) Euphorbiaceae-Acalypheae-Acalyphinae-Additamentum VII-Phyllanthoideae-Crotonoideae. In: Engler, A. (ed.) Das Pflanzenreich IV. 147. XVI - XVII. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig, pp. 1 - 231." type="book chapter" year="1924">Pax &amp; Hoffmann 1924: 63</bibRefCitation>
) the most. Both species share the presence of simple trichomes in the vegetative organs and penninerved leaves. However, the new species differs from 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF88DD1542DEF843FC8F9096" box="[645,791,1936,1963]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferdinandi">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD1542DEF843FC8F9096" box="[645,791,1936,1963]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">A. ferdinandi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the habit, being a suffruticose herb (vs. tree); the pistillate bracts have 7 teeth (vs. 13–15 teeth); the margin of the pistillate sepals is non-ciliate (vs. ciliate); the ovary surface is smooth and lacks glandular trichomes (vs. muricate surface with glandular trichomes). Finally, the distribution of these species is different, 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF88DD15413CF82FFE639F2A" box="[359,507,2044,2071]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferdinandi">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD15413CF82FFE639F2A" box="[359,507,2044,2071]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">A. ferdinandi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in the Atlantic slope, while 
<taxonomicName id="C6914D72FF88DD1543CCF82FFB9D9F2A" authorityName="Mart. Gord., Fragoso &amp; K. Velasco" authorityYear="2022" box="[919,1029,2044,2071]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="226" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amithii">
<emphasis id="33E5EAE3FF88DD1543CCF82FFB9D9F2A" box="[919,1029,2044,2071]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="226">A. amithii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in the Pacific slope.
</paragraph>
